ng immediacy as Jacques Bretel's record of Chauvency. He sat in a prime place, on the fourth step of the stand, and the reader sees and hears the action as if sitting at his shoulder - and eavesdrops on conversations, too. He gives remarkable insights into the surprising role played by song, and into how the whole event was perceived and understood. These intriguing works are invaluable source material for scholars not only of medieval chivalry and tournaments but also of festivities and performance.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aRing joustingxHistoryy13th centuryzFrance. 0aTournaments, MedievalxHistoryy13th centuryzFrance. 4aMedieval History. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aArthurian romance.  aFrench history.  afestivities.  ajousting.  amartial sport.  amedieval chivalry.  aperformance.  athirteenth-century tournaments.1 aBretel, Jacques, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBryant, Nigel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311143101740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781787449442?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781787449442423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781787449442/original  a978-3-11-143101-7  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles